<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>

<section xml:id="sec-applications-of-differentiation"
  xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
  <title>Applications</title>

  <introduction>
    <p>
      The Mean Value Theorem turns derivative information into comparisons of
      function values. This lets us read off monotonicity, detect local
      extrema, and prove qualitative facts about derivatives themselves. At
      the end of the section we include a brief preview of the Fundamental
      Theorem of Calculus, assuming the usual properties of the definite
      integral.
    </p>
  </introduction>

  <subsection xml:id="subsec-monotonicity-and-constant-functions">
    <title>Monotonicity</title>

    <proposition xml:id="prop-derivative-sign-and-monotonicity">
      <statement>
        <p>
          Let <m>I</m> be an open interval, and let <m>f \colon I \to \R</m>
          be differentiable on <m>I</m>.
        </p>
        <ol>
          <li>
            <p>
              The function <m>f</m> is increasing on <m>I</m> if and only if
              <m>f'(x) \ge 0</m> for every <m>x \in I</m>.
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              The function <m>f</m> is decreasing on <m>I</m> if and only if
              <m>f'(x) \le 0</m> for every <m>x \in I</m>.
            </p>
          </li>
        </ol>
      </statement>

      <proof>
        <p>
          We prove the increasing case; the decreasing case follows by
          applying the same argument to <m>-f</m>. First suppose that
          <m>f</m> is increasing on <m>I</m>. Fix <m>c \in I</m>. By
          Carathéodory's Criterion
          (<xref ref="prop-caratheodory-criterion"/>), there exists a function
          <m>\varphi \colon I \to \R</m>, continuous at <m>c</m>, such
          that <me>f(x)-f(c)=\varphi(x)(x-c)</me> for all <m>x \in I</m>,
          and <m>\varphi(c)=f'(c)</m>. For <m>x \neq c</m>, monotonicity of
          <m>f</m> gives <me>\varphi(x)=\frac{f(x)-f(c)}{x-c} \ge 0.</me>
          Since <m>\varphi</m> is continuous at <m>c</m>, it follows that
          <m>f'(c)=\varphi(c) \ge 0</m>.
        </p>

        <p>
          Conversely, suppose that <m>f'(x) \ge 0</m> for every <m>x
          \in I</m>.  Let <m>x_1,x_2 \in I</m> with <m>x_1 \lt x_2</m>. By
          the Mean Value Theorem (<xref ref="thm-mean-value-theorem"/>),
          applied to the restriction of <m>f</m> to <m>[x_1,x_2]</m>, there
          exists <m>c \in (x_1,x_2)</m> such that
          <me>f(x_2)-f(x_1)=f'(c)(x_2-x_1).</me> Since <m>f'(c)
          \ge 0</m> and <m>x_2-x_1 \gt 0</m>, we have <m>f(x_2)-f(x_1) \ge
          0</m>. Hence <m>f(x_1) \le f(x_2)</m>, so <m>f</m> is increasing
          on <m>I</m>.
        </p>
      </proof>
    </proposition>

    <proposition xml:id="prop-positive-derivative-implies-strictly-monotone">
      <statement>
        <p>
          Let <m>I</m> be an open interval, and let <m>f \colon I \to \R</m>
          be differentiable on <m>I</m>.
        </p>
        <ol>
          <li><p>If <m>f'(x) \gt 0</m> for every <m>x \in I</m>, then <m>f</m> is strictly increasing on <m>I</m>.</p></li>
          <li><p>If <m>f'(x) \lt 0</m> for every <m>x \in I</m>, then <m>f</m> is strictly decreasing on <m>I</m>.</p></li>
        </ol>
      </statement>

      <proof>
        <p>
          Again we prove only the increasing case. Let <m>x_1,x_2 \in I</m>
          with <m>x_1 \lt x_2</m>. By the Mean Value Theorem
          (<xref ref="thm-mean-value-theorem"/>), there exists
          <m>c \in (x_1,x_2)</m> such that
          <me>f(x_2)-f(x_1)=f'(c)(x_2-x_1).</me>
          Since <m>f'(c) \gt 0</m> and <m>x_2-x_1 \gt 0</m>, we get
          <m>f(x_2)-f(x_1) \gt 0</m>. Therefore <m>f</m> is strictly
          increasing on <m>I</m>.
        </p>
      </proof>
    </proposition>

    <example xml:id="eg-x-cubed-increasing-flat-at-zero">
      <statement>
        <p>
          The converse of
          <xref ref="prop-positive-derivative-implies-strictly-monotone"/> is
          false. The function <m>f(x)=x^3</m> is strictly increasing on
          <m>\R</m>, but <m>f'(0)=0</m>.
        </p>

        <figure xml:id="fig-x-cubed-flat-at-zero">
          <caption>The function <m>x^3</m> is strictly increasing even though its tangent is horizontal at <m>0</m>.</caption>
          <image width="48%">
            <shortdescription>The graph of y equals x cubed rises from left to right and has a horizontal tangent at the origin.</shortdescription>
            <latex-image>
\begin{tikzpicture}
\begin{axis}[
  width=7.4cm,
  height=5.8cm,
  axis lines=middle,
  xmin=-1.5, xmax=1.5,
  ymin=-1.8, ymax=1.8,
  xtick={-1,0,1},
  ytick={-1,0,1},
  xlabel={$x$},
  ylabel={$y$}
]
  \addplot[blue, thick, domain=-1.2:1.2, samples=200] {x^3};
  \addplot[red, thick, domain=-1.2:1.2] {0};
\end{axis}
\end{tikzpicture}
            </latex-image>
          </image>
        </figure>
      </statement>
    </example>

    <corollary xml:id="cor-derivative-zero-implies-constant">
      <statement>
        <p>
          Let <m>I</m> be an open interval, and let <m>f \colon I \to \R</m>
          be differentiable on <m>I</m>. If <m>f'(x)=0</m> for every
          <m>x \in I</m>, then <m>f</m> is constant on <m>I</m>.
        </p>
      </statement>

      <proof>
        <p>
          By <xref ref="prop-derivative-sign-and-monotonicity"/>, <m>f</m> is
          both increasing and decreasing on <m>I</m>. Hence <m>f</m> is
          constant on <m>I</m>.
        </p>
      </proof>
    </corollary>

    <p>
      The fact that the domain is an interval is essential here. For example,
      define <m>f \colon (-1,0)\cup(0,1) \to \R</m> by
      <me>f(x)=\begin{cases}
      -1 &amp; \text{if } x \lt 0,\\
      1 &amp; \text{if } x \gt 0.
      \end{cases}</me>
      Then <m>f'(x)=0</m> for every point of its domain, but <m>f</m> is not
      constant. What remains true in general is that <m>f</m> is constant on
      each interval component of its domain.
    </p>
  </subsection>

  <subsection xml:id="subsec-derivative-tests">
    <title>Derivative Tests for Extrema</title>

    <p>
      The sign of the derivative often reveals where extrema occur. The first
      derivative test uses only the sign pattern of <m>f'</m>. The second
      derivative test packages the same idea into a convenient condition at a
      single point.
    </p>

    <proposition xml:id="prop-first-derivative-test">
      <title>First Derivative Test</title>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Let <m>c \in (a,b)</m>, and let <m>f \colon (a,b) \to \R</m> be
          continuous on <m>(a,b)</m> and differentiable on
          <m>(a,b)\setminus\{c\}</m>.
        </p>
        <ol>
          <li>
            <p>
              If <m>f'(x) \ge 0</m> on <m>(a,c)</m> and <m>f'(x) \le 0</m> on
              <m>(c,b)</m>, then <m>c</m> is a maximum point of <m>f</m> on
              <m>(a,b)</m>.
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              If <m>f'(x) \le 0</m> on <m>(a,c)</m> and <m>f'(x) \ge 0</m> on
              <m>(c,b)</m>, then <m>c</m> is a minimum point of <m>f</m> on
              <m>(a,b)</m>.
            </p>
          </li>
        </ol>
        <p>
          If the inequalities are strict, then the corresponding extremum is
          strict.
        </p>
      </statement>

      <proof>
        <p>
          We prove the first statement. Let <m>x \in (a,c)</m>. The function
          <m>f</m> is continuous on <m>[x,c]</m> and differentiable on
          <m>(x,c)</m>, so the Mean Value Theorem
          (<xref ref="thm-mean-value-theorem"/>) gives a point
          <m>u_x \in (x,c)</m> such that
          <me>f(c)-f(x)=f'(u_x)(c-x).</me>
          Since <m>f'(u_x) \ge 0</m> and <m>c-x \gt 0</m>, we obtain
          <m>f(c)-f(x) \ge 0</m>, that is, <m>f(x) \le f(c)</m>.
        </p>

        <p>
          Similarly, if <m>y \in (c,b)</m>, then applying the Mean Value
          Theorem to <m>[c,y]</m> gives <m>v_y \in (c,y)</m> such that
          <me>f(y)-f(c)=f'(v_y)(y-c).</me>
          Since <m>f'(v_y) \le 0</m> and <m>y-c \gt 0</m>, we get
          <m>f(y) \le f(c)</m>. Therefore <m>f(x) \le f(c)</m> for every
          <m>x \in (a,b)</m>, so <m>c</m> is a maximum point of <m>f</m>. The
          strict case is identical, with <m>\ge</m> replaced by <m>\gt</m> and
          <m>\le</m> replaced by <m>\lt</m>. The second statement follows by
          applying the first to <m>-f</m>.
        </p>
      </proof>
    </proposition>

    <proposition xml:id="prop-second-derivative-test">
      <title>Second Derivative Test</title>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Let <m>f</m> be defined on a neighborhood of <m>x_0</m>, and suppose
          that <m>f</m> is twice differentiable at <m>x_0</m> with
          <m>f'(x_0)=0</m>.
        </p>
        <ol>
          <li><p>If <m>f''(x_0) \gt 0</m>, then <m>x_0</m> is a strict local minimum of <m>f</m>.</p></li>
          <li><p>If <m>f''(x_0) \lt 0</m>, then <m>x_0</m> is a strict local maximum of <m>f</m>.</p></li>
        </ol>
      </statement>

      <proof>
        <p>
          We prove the first statement. Apply Carathéodory's Criterion
          (<xref ref="prop-caratheodory-criterion"/>) to <m>f'</m> at
          <m>x_0</m>. Then there exists a function <m>\psi</m>, continuous at
          <m>x_0</m>, such that
          <me>f'(x)-f'(x_0)=\psi(x)(x-x_0)</me>
          for all <m>x</m> near <m>x_0</m>, and
          <m>\psi(x_0)=f''(x_0) \gt 0</m>. Since <m>f'(x_0)=0</m>, this becomes
          <me>f'(x)=\psi(x)(x-x_0).</me>
        </p>

        <p>
          Because <m>\psi</m> is continuous at <m>x_0</m> and
          <m>\psi(x_0) \gt 0</m>, there exists <m>\delta \gt 0</m> such that
          <m>\psi(x) \gt 0</m> whenever <m>|x-x_0| \lt \delta</m>. Hence
          <m>f'(x) \lt 0</m> on <m>(x_0-\delta,x_0)</m> and
          <m>f'(x) \gt 0</m> on <m>(x_0,x_0+\delta)</m>. By the First
          Derivative Test (<xref ref="prop-first-derivative-test"/>),
          <m>x_0</m> is a strict local minimum of <m>f</m>. The second
          statement follows by applying the first to <m>-f</m>.
        </p>
      </proof>
    </proposition>
  </subsection>

  <subsection xml:id="subsec-darboux-and-ftc-preview">
    <title>Darboux's Theorem and a Preview of the FTC</title>

    <theorem xml:id="thm-darboux-for-derivatives">
      <title>Darboux's Theorem</title>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Let <m>f \colon [a,b] \to \R</m> be differentiable on <m>[a,b]</m>.
          If <m>\lambda</m> lies between <m>f'(a)</m> and <m>f'(b)</m>, then
          there exists <m>c \in (a,b)</m> such that
          <me>f'(c)=\lambda.</me>
        </p>
      </statement>

      <proof>
	<p>
	  Replacing <m>f</m> by <m>x \mapsto f(x)-\lambda x</m>, it suffices
	  to prove the theorem in the case <m>\lambda=0</m>. Replacing
	  <m>f</m> by <m>-f</m> if necessary, we may further assume that
	  <m>f'(a) \lt 0 \lt f'(b)</m>.
	</p>

        <p>
	  Since <m>f</m> is differentiable at <m>a</m>, Carathéodory's
	  Criterion (<xref ref="prop-caratheodory-criterion"/>) gives a
	  function <m>\varphi_a</m>, continuous at <m>a</m>, such that
	  <me>
	    f(x)-f(a)=\varphi_a(x)(x-a)
	  </me>
	  for all <m>x \in [a,b]</m>, with <m>\varphi_a(a)=f'(a) \lt 0</m>.
	  Hence <m>\varphi_a(x) \lt 0</m> for all <m>x \gt a</m> sufficiently
	  close to <m>a</m>. Since also <m>x-a \gt 0</m>, it follows that
	  <m>f(x)-f(a) \lt 0</m> for such <m>x</m>. Therefore <m>a</m> is not
	  a minimum point of <m>f</m> on <m>[a,b]</m>.
        </p>

        <p>
	  A similar argument at <m>b</m> shows that <m>b</m> is not a minimum
	  point either. Indeed, Carathéodory's Criterion gives a function
	  <m>\varphi_b</m>, continuous at <m>b</m>, such that
	  <me>
	    f(x)-f(b)=\varphi_b(x)(x-b)
	  </me>
	  for all <m>x \in [a,b]</m>, with <m>\varphi_b(b)=f'(b) \gt 0</m>.
	  Thus <m>\varphi_b(x) \gt 0</m> for all <m>x \lt b</m> sufficiently
	  close to <m>b</m>. Since then <m>x-b \lt 0</m>, we obtain
	  <m>f(x)-f(b) \lt 0</m>. Hence <m>b</m> is not a minimum point of
	  <m>f</m>.
	</p>

	<p>
	  By the Extreme Value Theorem (<xref
	  ref="thm-extreme-value-theorem"/>), <m>f</m> attains its
	  minimum value at some point <m>c \in [a,b]</m>. Thus, we must
	  have <m>c \in (a,b)</m>. The Critical Point Theorem (<xref
	  ref="prop-critical-point-theorem"/>) then gives <m>f'(c)=0</m>, as
	  required.
	</p>
      </proof>
    </theorem>

    <p>
      Darboux's theorem shows that derivatives have the intermediate value
      property, even though derivatives need not be continuous. We now record
      one further application of the earlier results. This final part depends
      on the usual properties of the definite integral, which we have not yet
      developed systematically, so it should be viewed as a preview.
    </p>

    <proposition xml:id="prop-integral-mean-value-theorem">
      <title>Integral Mean Value Theorem</title>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Assume the basic properties of the definite integral. If
          <m>f \colon [a,b] \to \R</m> is continuous, then there exists
          <m>c \in [a,b]</m> such that
          <me>\int_a^b f(x)\,dx = f(c)(b-a).</me>
        </p>
      </statement>

      <proof>
        <p>
          By the Extreme Value Theorem
          (<xref ref="thm-extreme-value-theorem"/>), <m>f</m> attains an
          absolute minimum <m>m</m> and an absolute maximum <m>M</m> on
          <m>[a,b]</m>. Hence
          <me>m \le f(x) \le M \quad \text{for all } x \in [a,b].</me>
          Integrating gives
          <me>m(b-a) \le \int_a^b f(x)\,dx \le M(b-a).</me>
          Since <m>b-a \gt 0</m>,
          <me>m \le \frac{1}{b-a}\int_a^b f(x)\,dx \le M.</me>
          Because <m>f</m> is continuous on <m>[a,b]</m>, the
          Intermediate Value Theorem
          (<xref ref="thm-intermediate-value-theorem"/>) yields some
          <m>c \in [a,b]</m> such that
          <me>f(c)=\frac{1}{b-a}\int_a^b f(x)\,dx.</me>
          Multiplying by <m>b-a</m> gives the result.
        </p>
      </proof>
    </proposition>

    <theorem xml:id="thm-ftc-special-case">
      <title>Fundamental Theorem of Calculus (Special Case)</title>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Assume the basic properties of the definite integral. If
          <m>f \colon [a,b] \to \R</m> is continuous and
          <me>F(x)=\int_a^x f(t)\,dt,</me>
          then <m>F</m> is differentiable on <m>[a,b]</m> and
          <me>F'(x)=f(x)</me>
          for every <m>x \in [a,b]</m>.
        </p>
      </statement>

      <proof>
        <p>
          Fix <m>x \in [a,b]</m>. Let <m>h \neq 0</m> be small enough that
          <m>x+h \in [a,b]</m>. Then
          <me>F(x+h)-F(x)=\int_x^{x+h} f(t)\,dt.</me>
          By the Integral Mean Value Theorem
          (<xref ref="prop-integral-mean-value-theorem"/>), there exists a
          point <m>c_h</m> between <m>x</m> and <m>x+h</m> such that
          <me>\int_x^{x+h} f(t)\,dt = f(c_h)h.</me>
          Therefore
          <me>\frac{F(x+h)-F(x)}{h}=f(c_h).</me>
        </p>

        <p>
          Since <m>c_h</m> lies between <m>x</m> and <m>x+h</m>, we have
          <m>c_h \to x</m> as <m>h \to 0</m>. By continuity of <m>f</m>,
          <m>f(c_h) \to f(x)</m>. Hence
          <me>\lim_{h\to 0}\frac{F(x+h)-F(x)}{h}=f(x),</me>
          so <m>F'(x)=f(x)</m>.
        </p>
      </proof>
    </theorem>

    <p>
      This theorem is only a preview. In the integration chapter we prove the
      more general second form of the Fundamental Theorem of Calculus
      (<xref ref="thm-ftc-second-form"/>), where the integrand is assumed only
      to be Riemann integrable and the conclusion is differentiability at
      points of continuity of the integrand.
    </p>

    <corollary xml:id="cor-newton-leibniz-special-case">
      <statement>
        <p>
          Assume the basic properties of the definite integral. If
          <m>f \colon [a,b] \to \R</m> is continuous and <m>F</m> is any
          antiderivative of <m>f</m> on <m>[a,b]</m>, then
          <me>\int_a^b f(x)\,dx = F(b)-F(a).</me>
        </p>
      </statement>

      <proof>
        <p>
          Let <m>F_a(x)=\int_a^x f(t)\,dt</m>. By the Fundamental Theorem
          of Calculus (Special Case) (<xref ref="thm-ftc-special-case"/>),
          both <m>F</m> and <m>F_a</m> are antiderivatives of <m>f</m>
          on <m>[a,b]</m>. Hence <m>(F-F_a)'(x)=0</m> for every <m>x \in
          (a,b)</m>. By <xref ref="cor-derivative-zero-implies-constant"/>,
          the function <m>F-F_a</m> is constant on <m>(a,b)</m>. Since both
          <m>F_a</m> and <m>F</m> are continuous on <m>[a,b]</m>, it follows
          that <m>F-F_a</m> is constant on all of <m>[a,b]</m>.
        </p>

	<p>
	  Evaluating at <m>x=a</m>, we obtain
	  <me>
	    F(a)-F_a(a)=F(a),
	  </me>
	  because <m>F_a(a)=\int_a^a f(t)\,dt=0</m>. Therefore
	  <m>F(x)-F_a(x)=F(a)</m> for every <m>x \in [a,b]</m>. Setting
	  <m>x=b</m> gives
	  <me>
	    F(b)-\int_a^b f(t)\,dt = F(a),
	  </me>
	  and rearranging yields
	  <me>
	    \int_a^b f(x)\,dx = F(b)-F(a).
	  </me>
	</p>
      </proof>
    </corollary>

    <p>
      Likewise, the integration chapter proves the more general first form of
      the Fundamental Theorem of Calculus
      (<xref ref="thm-ftc-first-form"/>) and the corresponding
      Newton-Leibniz formula (<xref ref="cor-newton-leibniz-ftc"/>).
    </p>
  </subsection>
</section>
